# LaunchDarkly — Architectural Rules for AI-Assisted Development

## Provider Architecture (CRITICAL — hydration safety)

- `src/app/layout.js` MUST be a Server Component. Never add `'use client'` to it.
- The LaunchDarkly provider MUST live in `src/components/LDProviderWrapper.js` with `'use client'` at the top.
- Never call `asyncWithLDProvider` or any LD React SDK hook directly in `layout.js`.
- This pattern prevents Next.js App Router hydration mismatches.

## Client vs Server SDK boundaries

- `launchdarkly-react-client-sdk` — client components only (`'use client'` files)
- `@launchdarkly/node-server-sdk` — API routes only (`src/app/api/**`)
- `@launchdarkly/server-sdk-ai` — API routes only, never in React components
- Never import `@launchdarkly/node-server-sdk` or `@launchdarkly/server-sdk-ai` in any component

## Named imports (critical)

- CORRECT: `import { init } from '@launchdarkly/node-server-sdk'`
- WRONG:   `import init from '@launchdarkly/node-server-sdk'`

## Flag evaluation patterns

- Read flag values with `useFlags()` in React components
- Read flag values with `ldClient.variation()` AFTER `ldClient.identify()` resolves
- Never read `.variation()` before `identify()` resolves — values will reflect the old context
- `ldClient` can be null before the provider resolves — always null-check before calling any method

## AI Config patterns

- `aiConfig.model` is an object — use `aiConfig.model?.name`, never pass the object directly
- Always pass `userKey` and `userPlan` from the frontend to `/api/chat` so server-side targeting fires correctly
- Never hardcode user context in API routes

## Environment variables

- `NEXT_PUBLIC_LD_CLIENT_KEY` — browser-safe, used in `LDProviderWrapper.js`
- `LD_SERVER_KEY` — server only, never reference in any component
- `GOOGLE_AI_API_KEY` — server only, exact name (not GOOGLE_API_KEY)
- Never add `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix to server-only keys

## Toast / demo polish

- `<Toaster />` is placed once in `src/app/page.js` — never in individual components
- Use `useRef` guard for any `useEffect` toast that should fire exactly once (React 18 Strict Mode fires effects twice in development)

## New component checklist

When generating any new component:
1. Determine if it needs browser APIs or LD hooks → if yes, add `'use client'`
2. If it uses LD flags, import from `launchdarkly-react-client-sdk` only
3. Never import server-side LD packages into components